    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1957-05-02T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1957-05-02T00:00:00-05:00" n="191"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d191">
                <head>191. Memorandum of a Conference With the President, White House, Washington,
                    May 2, 1957<note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d191fn1">Source: Eisenhower
                        Library, Whitman File, DDE Diaries. Drafted by <persName corresp="#p_GCAJ1"
                            >Goodpaster</persName> on May 2. The conference was held following the
                            <gloss target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss> meeting. Another meeting was held
                        later that day with the President, <persName corresp="#p_SLL1"
                            >Strauss</persName>, <persName corresp="#p_SGC1">Gerard
                        Smith</persName>, <persName corresp="#p_WJJ1">Wadsworth</persName>, and
                            <persName corresp="#p_GCAJ1">Goodpaster</persName>, during which they
                        discussed the arguments raised against the <gloss target="#t_IAEA1"
                            >IAEA</gloss> statute. (Memorandum of conference by <persName
                            corresp="#p_GCAJ1">Goodpaster</persName>, May 3; <hi rend="italic"
                            >ibid</hi>.)</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1957-05-02">
                            <hi rend="italic">May 2, 1957</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="participants">
                    <head>OTHERS PRESENT</head>
                    <item>Secretary <persName corresp="#p_HCA1">Herter</persName>
                    </item>
                    <item>Admiral <persName corresp="#p_SLL1">Strauss</persName>
                    </item>
                    <item>Governor <persName corresp="#p_AS1">Adams</persName>
                    </item>
                    <item>Mr. <persName>Harlow</persName>
                    </item>
                    <item>Ambassador <persName corresp="#p_WJJ1">Wadsworth</persName>
                    </item>
                    <item>General <persName corresp="#p_GCAJ1">Goodpaster</persName>
                    </item>
                </list>
                <p>The meeting was concerned with the resistance being manifested in the Senate to
                    prompt ratification of the International Atomic Energy Agency treaty. Admiral
                        <persName corresp="#p_SLL1">Strauss</persName> reviewed certain of the
                    questions of challenges being raised against the treaty—that it is a “give away”
                    (which it is not); that third countries would be enabled to develop atomic
                    weapons (they will in any event, and the treaty provides a means of instituting
                    inspection); that Red China can join the Agency (we retain the right to pull out
                    at any time on due notice—here the President added that to get in they would
                    have to subject themselves to inspection with much of the same result as his own
                    air inspection proposal); that the Agency is not necessary since we have
                    bilateral agreements (we have these with some, not all, free world countries,
                    and many countries are not subject to inspection); that the satellites could
                    obtain our contributions of fissionable material (in fact, we can direct our
                    contributions to countries with whom we have bilateral treaties); that the
                    treaty, once approved, could be amended to include provisions adverse to U.S.
                    interest (amendment requires a ⅔ vote, we would be free to drop out of the
                    organization in such case, and amendment could only bind us upon our ratifying
                    it).</p>
                <p>After some further discussion it was agreed, and the President arranged by phone,
                    for the President to meet with Senators <persName corresp="#p_KWF1"
                        >Knowland</persName> and <persName corresp="#p_HBB1">Hickenlooper</persName>
                    on this matter at 11 o’clock tomorrow.<note n="2" xml:id="d191fn2">
                        <persName corresp="#p_EDD1">Eisenhower</persName> met with <persName
                            corresp="#p_KWF1">Knowland</persName> and <persName corresp="#p_HBB1"
                            >Hickenlooper</persName> on May 3 from 11:02 to 11:42 a.m. (<hi
                            rend="italic">ibid.,</hi>
                        <persName corresp="#p_EDD1">Eisenhower</persName> Records, President’s
                        Appointment Book for 1957), but no record of their conversation has been
                        found in the Eisenhower Library or Department of State files.</note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="strong">G</hi>
                        <lb/>
                        <hi rend="italic">Brigadier General, <gloss target="#t_USA1">USA</gloss>
                        </hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
